div.div: @jakeyounglol You may also need to install .Net Framework 4.8.1 manually, as it introduced Arm64 support for the .Net Framework which I set it to compile and target to

Well this seems to be kind of difficult to get working correctly. After applying the fix mentioned here https://github.com/dotnet/sdk/issues/28419 it does indeed compile Arm64 Versions of ViVeTool GUI, the Feature Scanner and a WebView2 DLL, although all other DLLs, including Mach2 seem to be x86-64 only so it seems that you are required to rely on a x64 to Arm64 Translation Layer Compiling for Arm64 also seems to introduce a Bug where it is not compiling any Localised Resources, removing any Multi-Language Support
The ARM64 compiled Version is here: ViVeTool_GUI_ARM64.zip
Commented on #61 please add arm64 support
Hmmm Debugging Arm64 Builds of ViVeTool GUI would be a challenge because I don't own a Arm64 Device capable of running Windows, but I'll try to get a Arm64 Build working later today
